<a href="viewtopic.php?p=83983#83983"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Wed Nov 03, 2004 2:39 pm</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">Well i guess this would be better if the topic were 'high level bards'.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Well, I was not a raiding enchanter for a very long time, and I mezzed multiples, and singles A LOT in LDON, on hards missing mezzes meant death. Also quite a bit on KT trials. I rarely ever had a bard in my groups, and was always glad when I did. That freed me and him up to do other things. The nice thing about having a good enchanter in the group pre-OoW was you didn't NEED a bard, or a monk, etc.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
For one, how the hell did you need to mezz mobs in the KT trials?  I've soloed a good bit in vxed and done numerous tipts, and with the exception of the ghosts in tipt i'm not sure how you can possibly get an adds in the trials.  Hell, even without memming lull virtually everything would be single.  Mezzing was good in ldon, sebilis, lower guk, etc but those were all long ago.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Well, I don't know about you, but I'd slap a tash and a slow on the mobs right after they were all locked down, and yes, it is, all around still a better slow.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
What mobs are you locking down was the point.  One mob, one slow...unless you're goofing off thats all that should be occurring assuming competent pulling.  Slow mitigation narrows the gap such that bard slow is just as good.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">And of course, all bards who love grouping ever so much are Time and Tacvi flagged. I could probably count the amount of active bards on my server with these weapons on my server on two hands.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Then fix the itemization.  A class-only item is a part of class balance and its rarity should not be taken into consideration unless its unique or something.  More and more bards will be getting these so even if one considers it rare now (and i sure wouldn't, there are huge numbers of bards with these on my server at least) it won't always be.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">This is true. However in a raid I'll take all the resists I can get. If I can get something that stacks with GoD I'll take it and be happy. In just about every grouping situation I've been in bard resist was massive overkill and not that necessary.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
A lot of people say this, but most of them aren't tanks who get railed by kyv/ukun procs with no bard in group and can almost ignore them with a bard for pov.  Other classes' resist spells make almost no difference, but pov makes it a completely different ballgame.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Most melees I know would kill for 50 atk. Spending massive amounts of money for items that add that much. If the effect on salik is broken, then it needs to be fixed, of course. It should be stackable as well.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
50 atk just isn't that much anymore.  The effect on salik DOES stack but its so minimal as to be almost unnoticeable.  Cleave items are easily attainable for raiders and they add as much or more than something that is supposedly a balancing feature of this class.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">As an enchanter, I'm sure you take for granted the fact that you get a VoQ or a clicky tranq followed by a gather mana every time you're rezzed. Others aren't so fortunate. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I take most buffs for granted because a buffbot can always be brought in.  KEI is especially easy to take for granted because of its duration.  Deep inside instanced trials it matters.  Xp grinding in mpg or something it does not.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">They'd have to, especially if they're running off to pull the next mob at 50%. I would think a bard would have to be EXTREMELY well geared to have the same DPS as even a naked enchanter when doing that.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
If you're comparing a bard who is pulling to an enchanter doing nothing but slow/tash/nuke then yes the enchanter will most likely win.  However, that isn't comparing 'apples to apples'.  The comparison that makes sense is the sustained damage capability of the bard (ie their normal melee and the contributions they can reasonably make to the damage dealing of a standard group) versus that of the enchanter (ie considering damage/mana and mana/sec and pet damage).  It doesn't take extremely good gear to outdo enchanter damage.  Nuking in everquest is EXTREMELY poor sustained damage.  The number look pretty and everyone oohs and ahs about big crits, but the only numbers that matter for sustained are the efficiency and the caster's mana regen.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
